Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objectives¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer hascontacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

In [22]:
#Plotting elbow curve for finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(data_kmeans)
    prediction=model.predict(data_kmeans)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(data_kmeans, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / data_kmeans
                           .shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[22]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
From the plot, the error rate start to minimized from k = 3 and the first steepest decline occurs for this k . We will test for k between 3 and 6

# generate the linkage matrix and plots for atleast 4 linkage methods
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import cophenet, dendrogram, linkage
linkages = ['single','complete','average','ward']
for i in linkages:
    Z = linkage(data_hier, i, metric='euclidean')
    plt.figure(figsize=(25, 10))
    #fig, ax_lst = plt.subplots(1, 1)
    dendrogram(Z)
    plt.show()

In the cell above, the dendrograms shown are for 'single','complete','average','ward' linkages in top to bottom order

In [36]:
#Calculate cophenetic coefficient for atleast 4 linkage methods and store to a dataframe

from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist  #Pairwise distribution between data points

linkages = ['single','complete','average','ward']
cophenetic_coef = []
for i in linkages:
    Z = linkage(data_hier, i, metric='euclidean')
    cc,coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(data_hier))
    cophenetic_coef.append((i,cc))
cophenetic_coef_df = pd.DataFrame({"CopCoefficient":cophenetic_coef, "Linkage":linkages})
cophenetic_coef_df
#The one with the hieghest coph is the best
Out[36]:

From the above dataframe, the Linkage with highest cophenetic coefficient would be used. In this case, the average linkage method with about 90% cophenetic coefficient would be used. In other words, the eucleadean and dendrogramic distance are closest for the average linkage method

The box plots in cells 43 and 44 indicates that the hierachical and kmeans clustering carried out in this project produce predictions that are very closely matched. For each variable, the amount of entries clustered into a group is the same when compared between the two methods. Even the outliers in the clusters are equally reproduced. The only observed difference is in the placement of the labels which could result from the difference in random state that was used in fitting the clustering method. Flipping a specific variable box plots produced by Hierachical Clustering (Cell 44) about a vertical axis (360 degrees) produces its exact counterpart that was produced using Kmeans Clustering (Cell43). This means the labels were reversed

plt.title('Hierarchical Predicted Classes')
sns.scatterplot(x='Total_Credit_Cards', y='Avg_Credit_Limit', style = 'heir_label', data=data_hier, ax=ax2)

plt.show()

Considering the predicted plot of classes of two variables ("Avg_Credit_Limit" and "Total_Credit_Cards") in cell 45, one can see that the formed clusters are closely matched for the two methods. The Avg_Credit_Limit for kmeans predicted classes was reproduced in a similar clusters for Hierarchical predicted classes with only the labels 1 and 2 interchanged in position

7. Analyse the clusters formed, tell us how is one cluster different from another and answer all the key questions. (10 marks)¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

  1. By using kmeans clustering techniques including analysing elbow curve and box plots (cell 22 to 33), the different segments of customers were observed to be 3 segments. We will call them Customer 1, Customer 2 and Customer 3.

  2. From box plot in cell 44, one can deduce the following:

    Customer 0:Medium user of Credit Cards, contacts bank regularly (physically) but does not use online services regularly.

Customer 1:High user of Credit Cards, uses online services the most but doesnt contact bank regularly.

Customer 2:Low user of Credit Cards, contacts bank regularly (calls) and medium user of online services.

  3. These recommendations are made assuming there is a very low risk of a default, where increase in credit limit will lead to more interest and as a result more returns to the bank:

     For Customer 0: Advertise benefits of using online tools such as flexibility, rebates etc and also sensitize customers on the benefits of not defaulting.

 For Customer 1: Potential high income earners, they should be targeted with ad campaigns for high value low risk investments eg investment in the bank's stock.

 For Customer 2: Create incentives to make this category of customers increase their credit limit e.g offering more friendly repayment plans such as yearly financing. Also advise customer to use more online tools in order not to miss out on important ad campaigns.
